Text.Value: We need to get you out of this pact.
She'll be gone soon enough. Do this mission, and Mizora will free you from the pact.
Though to hear her tell it, it was my choice to keep her a secret.

EditorData.logicalname: Mizora made it sound like Wyll kept her a secret on purpose
Mizora passed judgment - no rescue mission

Text.Value: What did you expect? She's a devil. Hardly the paragon of honesty.
And it means everything to me.
One of the mindless blobs clawing at demons on the front lines of the Blood War.
We can beat her, if we put our worms together.
All these years, you'd think it's a lesson I'd have well learned.
What are the terms of the pact?
... not Zariel's victims, not innocent tieflings.
A cruel bind. Mizora is like a spider, and you the enwebbed fly.
Before I was infected, I could even call hellbeasts and summon festering clouds.
I deserve that. Consider me properly shamed.
Just look at me. I did what was right. And Mizora made me pay for it.
What are the terms of your pact?
You should get out of this pact.

EditorData.logicalname: Mizora passed judgment - no rescue mission

Text.Value: Yes, unless I find a way to free myself from my devil's talons.
You were exploited, you were bound. I was not.
I didn't even have a pact, and I was captured by one for ten years.
... not people like you. I swear, I didn't know.
Mizora certainly plays for keeps, anyway.
And you shouldn't be.
She could kill me, for one - and that's not the worst of it.
Mizora's set me on fiends inside and outside the Hells. She's never ordered a rescue.
We can have all for it, but it won't so much as chip one of her nailed claws: She'll escape to the Hells. And if we succeeded, my life would be taken in exchange.
But I'll say this: the moment I pacted myself to Mizora I have not regretted for a heartbeat. It was my proudest deed.
So you're bound to be a lemure, no matter what?
Or so I thought - until Karlach.
Why didn't you tell me about Mizora before now?
We'll see if it's worth it. We might need the pact, after all.
Gods, she makes a mockery of everything the Blade stands for. Such an arsehole.

EditorData.NodeContext: Subtly exasperated. Not leaning too far into anger or vexation.

Text.Value: Not a one. All that matters is that we free it.
But you got out, you did the unimaginable. You brilliant, impossible woman.
Either we find it - or I'm made a mindless blob clawing at demons on the front lines of the Blood War.
I did the bidding of my abuser for so long, and it only made me weaker.
... not this. Not Zariel's victims, not innocent tieflings.
Thank you - for sticking your neck out for me. I mean it.
We can, I'm sure of it. How glad I am that you see me as more than my patron's pet.
I'd be hunting devils and demons, she said. Traitors and hypocrites - heartless evils of all sorts - but not...
I always knew what my future held, and I know I chose right.

EditorData.NodeContext: Clears throat at end of line, he physically cannot finish.

Text.Value: Gods damn her straight back to the Hells.
Let me guess: This pact is what caused the rift between you and your father.
Half-truths and devil pacts? You're not worth the soil you stand on.
My contract is very clear I can bring Mizora no harm: she'll have to let me out of my pact willingly.
I thought you were supposed to hunt devils. Doesn't this violate your contract?
Not just rot. I'd have to fight.
I was a magistrate once, I could see if you missed any loopholes in your contract.
You're right, of course. Somewhere, there must a weak link, a loophole, an exploit.
Can't we just attack her the next time she pops up?
The same thought crossed my mind. I am only to hunt the infernal, the demonic, and the heartless.
Ah. The one little question that put me out of house and home.
A warrior? Hardly. A single lemure is worth less than a maggot. Only in swarms are they ever useful.
Karlach showed us the truth. And I refused to see it.
Eh. Knowing a devil's deal, you would retain your senses. No comfort, I suppose.

EditorData.NodeContext: Wyll says if he fails his contract, he'll be turned into a 'mindless blob'. Jaheira is trying and failing to find the bright side.

Text.Value: It was worth the sacrifice. All I can give you on that is my solemn word.
What did you expect? She's a devil. Hardly the paragon of honesty.
I'd be hunting devils and demons, Mizora said. Traitors and hypocrites - heartless evils of all sorts - but not...
It's not like you have a choice. Do the mission, or rot in the Hells.
She won't let me go without making a fuss. Trust me on that.
This was a path I chose, thinking I knew all the terms. I thought wrong.
Were I a less considerate man, this is where I'd remind you of the importance of reading the fine print. But fear not - I shall bite my tongue.
Why obey her at all? What's the worst she could do?
You've been turned into a devil. An appropriate punishment, I'd say.
It's... not unrelated. I wish I could tell you more.
As I always have.
She won't touch you, unless there's something there for her to take. Don't give her so much as an inkling there might be.
A possibility that's kept me awake countless nights.
Fail, and I'm made a mindless blob clawing at demons on the front lines of the Blood War.
But - I'm not going to celebrate 'til I'm actually free. I can feel Mizora scheming, plotting.
The only way out is if I can out-bargain her. We're standing here with nothing but the clothes on our backs and the worms in our heads.
But nowhere was it stated that I can't help one.
That has been its tragedy. I've saved so many with the talents of the Blade.
Any idea who this devil is that needs freeing?
You are everything you accused me of being. I'm not sorry for you.
Yes, unless Mizora actually fulfils her promise and sets me free.
Let me guess: This pact is what caused the rift between you and your father.
It's Mizora who grants me the power to conjure armour and cast eldritch blasts.
Why obey her at all? What could she do that's worse than she already has?
Damn it all, what have I done?
I'd count my lucky stars for it - but I reckon luck is on holiday. I'm only alive because my patron still has use for me.
You warned me about Raphael, but are pacted to Mizora? What a fraud.
I wish I'd had a piece of your drive aeons ago, before I got years deep into blindly obeying Mizora.
You are everything you accused Karlach of being. I'm not sorry for you.
There must be some loophole in the contract that lets you out.
You're lucky she didn't take your soul when she came.
No, Wyll. Not you. I won't let that happen. Not ever.

EditorData.NodeContext: Wyll is talking about becoming a soldier for Zariel, which is very triggering for Karlach.

Text.Value: My oath forbids me from uttering her very name - not unless she's revealed herself to you.
How in the Hells did you get involved with Mizora?
But I promise you, every thrust of my blade and every flame I sparked was for the good of the Coast.
It's not going to happen. You mean too much to the Sword Coast.
I'm sorry, Karlach.
I'm so sorry to give you another reason to sleep restlessly, but it's my burden to bear.
Mizora serves Zariel. The Archduchess of  the Hells. Why would  you sell your soul to her?
I just fear what she will do to us next.
Visions can't always be trusted. You did what you thought was right.
An actual hero. One of the few.
The Blade of Frontiers has some explaining to do.
That's horrifying. I'm so sorry.
Without the pact, I'm just a man. What good is my blade then, when it's too dull to split monsters? What good is a flame when a mere breath snuffs it out?
You're lucky she didn't take your soul when she came.
I'll say what I can. But it won't be enough.
I'd be hunting devils and demons, Mizora said. Traitors and hypocrites - heartless evils of all sorts - but not...
There could well be: she has the blighted thing, what I know of it is simply what has engraved itself upon my memory.
My, my. She really has you by the unmentionables, doesn't she?
Thank you - for sticking your neck out for me. I mean it. But - I'm not going to celebrate 'til I'm actually free.
But I don't have half a clue where to start, other than play her games, and play by the rules. That's the only language devils listen to.
You warned me about Raphael, but are pacted to Mizora? What a fraud.
Leave.
I bear the image of one, at least. But my heart is the same.
I can't utter the terms or circumstances of the pact. I can tell you most all else - but the pact? I'm forbidden, unless Mizora permits it.
I can already feel her scheming. She won't let me go without a fuss, trust me on this.
The Blade of Frontiers has some explaining to do.
*Warlock pacts tend to be unforgiving, from what you know of them. Wyll was lucky he didn't face a more severe punishment.*
